== Isotopes ==
{{main|Isotopes of astatine}}
Astatine has 33 known [[isotope]]s, all of which are [[radioactive]]; the range of their mass numbers is from 191 to 223. There exist also 23 [[metastable]] [[excited state]]s. The longest-lived isotope is &lt;sup&gt;210&lt;/sup&gt;At, which has a [[half-life]] of 8.1 hours; the shortest-lived known isotope is &lt;sup&gt;213&lt;/sup&gt;At, which has a half-life of 125 [[nanoseconds]].&lt;ref name =&quot;nubas&quot;&gt;{{cite journal  | last = Audi | first = Georges  | title = The NUBASE Evaluation of Nuclear and Decay Properties  | journal = Nuclear Physics A  | volume = 729  | pages = 3–128 | publisher = Atomic Mass Data Center  | year = 2003 | doi=10.1016/j.nuclphysa.2003.11.001 |bibcode = 2003NuPhA.729....3A }}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Applications ==
The least stable isotopes of astatine have no practical applications other than scientific study due to their extremely short life, but heavier isotopes have medical uses. Astatine-211 is an alpha emitter with a physical half-life of 7.2 h. These features have led to its use in [[radiation therapy]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | journal = Journal Nuclear Medicine | title = Overcoming the Obstacles to Clinical Evaluation of 211At-Labeled Radiopharmaceuticals | first = D. S. | last = Wilbur  | date=1 October 2001| volume = 42 | pages = 1516–1518 | url = http://jnm.snmjournals.org/cgi/reprint/42/10/1516 | issue = 10 }}&lt;/ref&gt; An investigation of the efficacy of astatine-211–tellurium colloid for the treatment of experimental malignant ascites in mice reveals that this alpha-emitting radiocolloid can be curative without causing undue toxicity to normal tissue. By comparison, [[beta particle|beta]]-emitting [[phosphorus-32]] as colloidal chromic phosphate had no antineoplastic activity. The most compelling explanation for this striking difference is the dense ionization and short range of action associated with alpha-emission. These results have important implications for the development and use of alpha-emitters as radiocolloid therapy for the treatment of human tumors.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | journal = Science | year = 1981 | volume = 212 | issue = 4492 | pages = 340–341 | doi = 10.1126/science.7209534 | title = Astatine-211--tellurium radiocolloid cures experimental malignant ascites | last = Bloomer | first = W. D. | url = http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/212/4492/340 | pmid = 7209534 | last2 = McLaughlin | first2 = WH | last3 = Neirinckx | first3 = RD | last4 = Adelstein | first4 = SJ | last5 = Gordon | first5 = PR | last6 = Ruth | first6 = TJ | last7 = Wolf | first7 = AP|bibcode = 1981Sci...212..340B }}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Precautions ==

Since astatine is extremely radioactive, it should be handled with extreme care.  Because of its extreme rarity, it is not likely that the general public will be exposed.

Astatine is a halogen, and standard precautions apply.  It is reactive, sharing similar chemical characteristics with iodine.

There are toxicologic studies of astatine-211 on mice indicating that [[radioactive poisoning]] is the major effect on living organisms.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | doi = 10.1177/096032718800700602 | title = Toxicity of Astatine-211 in the Mouse | year = 1988 | author = Cobb, L.M. | journal = Human &amp; Experimental Toxicology | volume = 7 | pages = 529 | last2 = Harrison | first2 = A. | last3 = Butler | first3 = S.A. | issue = 6}}&lt;/ref&gt;

